50|$|A trailer bike is {{attached}} to a bicycle at either the <b>seatpost</b> or on a special rear rack by a linkage that allows for pivoting. Alternatively, the hitch mechanism may rotate using the <b>seatpost</b> as the pivot. The attachment may include a quick-release option.|$|E
50|$|Giant frames were {{originally}} made of 6061 (ALUXX) aluminium alloy and were also characterised by bladed forks and <b>seatposts</b> to reduce air resistance. Frames came in three sizes (small, medium, and large), with riders fitted {{through the use}} of stems and <b>seatposts</b> of different lengths. Another Mike Burrows innovation that was featured on the original TCR (Total Compact Road) bikes included a height-adjustable stem, later removed from road racing bicycles due to flex under heavy loads.|$|R
